  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_246024860" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/246024860" />
    <a title="John" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2095414-john"><img alt="John" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1317221772p2/2095414.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/246024860?book_show_action=true">Dec 12, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="John" class="user" itemprop="url" name="John" href="/user/show/2095414-john">John</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2095414-john?shelf=2016">2016</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer246024860" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18306846647408395015">Mander is one of the earliest critics of television, writing this book in 1977. Mander began in the ad industry, and slowly awoke to the horrible power that advertisers have over their audience--the ability to &quot;persuade and dominate minds by interfering in people&apos;s thinking patterns.&quot; But it was when he began feeling conflicted over working for clients whose interests were in direct opposition to one another.<br/><br/>This awakening then opened up to a new awareness to the power of television and the way </span>
  <span id="freeText18306846647408395015" style="display:none">Mander is one of the earliest critics of television, writing this book in 1977. Mander began in the ad industry, and slowly awoke to the horrible power that advertisers have over their audience--the ability to "persuade and dominate minds by interfering in people's thinking patterns." But it was when he began feeling conflicted over working for clients whose interests were in direct opposition to one another.<br /><br />This awakening then opened up to a new awareness to the power of television and the way it mediates experience and the world around us with a strange power. He sets his thesis out very plainly in the beginning of the book, arguing that television itself "is not reformable." <br /><br />He writes, "Far from being 'neutral,' television itself predetermines who shall use it, how they will use it, what effects it will have on individual lives, and, if it continues to be widely used, what sorts of political forms will inevitably emerge." p. 45<br /><br />His first argument is not specifically aimed against television, but is concerned with the way science and technology have transformed the way we look at the world around us, and the power "experts" and scientists have upon our minds. We "no longer trust personal observation, even of the self-evident, until it is confirmed by scientific or technological institutions," and we "have lost insight into natural processes." p. 54 Mander's concern here, is that television has accelerated these defects, and papered over them, priming the population for autocracy. <br /><br />The second argument is an expansion of the first--the fear that "the controllers" will further concentrate power into the hands of the few, further empowering a monolithic culture. While there is some truth to this argument, his argument is compromised, and ultimately nullified because of his bad economics.<br /><br />His third argument is interesting, the "Effects of Television on the Human Being." He beings by exploring the physical effects of television, which is quite interesting--discussing the physics of a cathode ray tube. He moves on to the psychological effects equating television with hypnosis.<br /><br />His final argument is about the "Inherent Biases of Television." This is the best part of the book, by far, where he shows the medium of television constrains itself to specific biases. This means that television shows will be biased toward the type of content that is most effectively communicated by the medium. <br /><br />Toward the end of the book he lists thirty-three specific biases, including:<br /><br />"1) War is better television that peace."<br />2) Violence is better TV than nonviolence.<br />6) Political movements with single charismatic leaders are also more suitable and efficient for television. [Hello Barack Obama and Donald Trump!]<br />7) The one is easier than the many. The personality or symbol is easier than the philosophy.<br />9) Superficiality is easier than depth.<br />12) Feelings of conflict, and their embodiment in actions, work better on television than feelings of agreement and their embodiment in calm and unity.<br />13) Lust is better television that satisfaction.<br />21) The bizarre always gets more attention on television than the usual.<br />32) The finite is easier than the infinite."<br /><br />There are many powerful arguments in the book, though it is unfortunately compromised by a lot of fallacious argumentation and liberal diatribes. But the finale is powerful. One of the best things in the book is this summary:<br /><br />"Television limits and confines human knowledge. It changes the way humans receive information from the world. In place of natural multidimensional information reception, it offers a very narrow-gauged sense experience, diminishing the amount and kind of information people receive. Television keeps awareness contained within its own rigid channels, a tiny fraction of the natural information field. Because of television we believe we know more, but we know less." p. 349<br /><br />Much more could be said of television, and I was disappointed that Mander didn't say it. But, credit must be given to him for pioneering the criticism of television all the way back in 1977. Television is a slavemaster, holding its regular parishioners in bondage. This book helped begin the critical evaluation of television, but Neil Postman's "Amusing Ourselves to Death" is a much shorter, and more powerful argument against it. </span>
  <a data-text-id="18306846647408395015" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


